{"id":"2011.05966","submitter":"Spencer Hill","authors":"Spencer A. Hill, Simona Bordoni, Jonathan L. Mitchell","title":"Solsticial Hadley Cell ascending edge theory from supercriticality","comments":"15 pages, 7 figures, revised for Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences","journal-ref":"Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences 2021","doi":"10.1175/JAS-D-20-0341.1","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  How far the Hadley circulation's ascending branch extends into the summer\nhemisphere is a fundamental but incompletely understood characteristic of\nEarth's climate. Here, we present a predictive, analytical theory for this\nascending edge latitude based on the extent of supercritical forcing.\nSupercriticality sets the minimum extent of a large-scale circulation based on\nthe angular momentum and absolute vorticity distributions of the hypothetical\nstate were the circulation absent. We explicitly simulate this\nlatitude-by-latitude radiative-convective equilibrium (RCE) state. Its\ndepth-averaged temperature profile is suitably captured by a simple analytical\napproximation that increases linearly with $\\sin\\varphi$, where $\\varphi$ is\nlatitude, from the winter to the summer pole. This, in turn, yields a one-third\npower-law scaling of the supercritical forcing extent with the thermal Rossby\nnumber. In moist and dry idealized GCM simulations under solsticial forcing\nperformed with a wide range of planetary rotation rates, the ascending edge\nlatitudes largely behave according to this scaling.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Nov 2020 18:33:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 2 Mar 2021 23:59:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-15"}
