{"id":"2011.06008","submitter":"Uri Kol","authors":"Uri Kol","title":"Subleading BMS Charges and The Lorentz Group","comments":"v2: references added","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th gr-qc hep-ph math-ph math.MP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The extended BMS group includes supertranslation, dual supertranslation and\nLorentz transformations. The generators of these symmetries can be classified\naccording to their parity into \"electric\" and \"magnetic\" types. Using a\nmultipole expansion of gravitational sources in the Newman-Penrose formalism,\nwe associate each one of these charges with a particular moment. At leading\norder, the \"electric\" and \"magnetic\" monopole moments correspond respectively\nto supertranslations and dual supertranslations. At the first subleading order,\nthe \"electric\" and \"magnetic\" dipole moments correspond respectively to boosts\nand rotations, therefore comprising the entire Lorentz group. Electric-magnetic\ntype of duality then rotates the boost and rotation generators into each other.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Nov 2020 19:00:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 17 Aug 2021 01:15:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-18"}
{"id":"2011.06009","submitter":"Barbara Soda","authors":"Jonathan Oppenheim, Carlo Sparaciari, Barbara \\v{S}oda, Zachary\n  Weller-Davies","title":"Objective trajectories in hybrid classical-quantum dynamics","comments":"35 pages (Quantum format), 8 figures; appendix 6 pages. Accepted for\n  publication in Quantum","journal-ref":"Quantum 7, 891 (2023)","doi":"10.22331/q-2023-01-03-891","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph hep-th","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Consistent dynamics which couples classical and quantum degrees of freedom\nexists, provided it is stochastic. This dynamics is linear in the hybrid state,\ncompletely positive and trace preserving. One application of this is to study\nthe back-reaction of quantum fields on space-time which does not suffer from\nthe pathologies of the semi-classical equations. Here we introduce several toy\nmodels in which to study hybrid classical-quantum evolution, including a qubit\ncoupled to a particle in a potential, and a quantum harmonic oscillator coupled\nto a classical one. We present an unravelling approach to calculate the\ndynamics, and provide code to numerically simulate it. Unlike the purely\nquantum case, the trajectories (or histories) of this unravelling can be\nunique, conditioned on the classical degrees of freedom for discrete\nrealisations of the dynamics, when different jumps in the classical degrees of\nfreedom are accompanied by the action of unique operators on the quantum\nsystem. As a result, the ``measurement postulate'' of quantum theory is not\nneeded; quantum systems become classical because they interact with a\nfundamentally classical field.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Nov 2020 19:00:34 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 28 Dec 2022 19:33:42 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 2 Jan 2023 07:18:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-04"}
